summary.seg: This manuscript, copied in the years around 1500, is a Greek Miscellany whose largest single component is the collection of short biographies of ancient philosophers by the 3rd-century CE writer Diogenes Laertios. It also contains a range of ancient and medieval grammatical and rhetorical texts and excerpts, primarily commentaries on the works of the ancient rhetoricians Hermogenes and Aphthonios by the leading late 13th-early 14th century Byzantine classical scholar Maximos Planoudes. Other contents include commentaries on mythology and the most recent component, a brief excerpt from a theological text by Georgios Scholarios (c. 1405-c. 1472), the scholar and official who became Patriarch of Constantinople as Gennadios II.

The manuscript was copied by three different copyists, whose work is interspersed throughout the manuscript. One of these has been identified as Georgios Moschos, a scholar from Corfu who copied manuscripts there before moving to Italy towards the end of the 15th century, where he worked in Ferrara and Mirandola, taught rhetoric and medicine and did editorial work for the great Venetian printer of Greek texts Aldus Manutius. Another has been identified as one Ioannes, a collaborator of Georgios, who has been tentaively identified as his father Ioannes Moschos. A variety of other manuscripts copied by both men have been identified, mostly classical texts.

supportDesc.foliation: The manuscript is foliated with the numbers [i-v] + 1-244 + [vi], in pencil, in Arabic numerals, recto, upper right.

collation.p: The manuscript consists of 35 quires, of which one is a single bifolio, six are binia, three are ternia and the rest are quaternia.

handNote.p: ff. ff. 1r-6r, line 1, 104r-127v, 132r-240r were copied by Georgios Moschos (Hand A) (RGK I 67, II 88, III 111), in a mixed minuscule script, in brown ink, slanting slightly to the right, with moderate variation in letter size.

Syllabic abbreviations and superscript word endings appear throughout the line. Breathings are round and mute iota is absent. There is decorative use of the double dot. Accents are sometimes joined to letters and abbreviations.
The modern eta, modern nu, sigma telikon and loop epsilon are present.
Punctuation used includes the middle and upper points, lower and middle commas, question mark and full stop.
Headings are in the same style in red ink.
ff. 19r-26r, 27r-37v, 39r-42r, 43r-52v, 54r-81v were copied by Hand B, in a mixed minuscule script, in brown ink, slanting slightly to the right, with moderate variation in letter size.

Syllabic abbreviations and superscript word endings appear throughout the line. Breathings are round and mute iota is absent. There is decorative use of the double dot. Accents are sometimes joined to letters and abbreviations.
The modern eta, modern nu, sigma telikon and loop epsilon are present.
Punctuation used includes the middle and upper points, lower and middle commas, question mark and full stop.
Headings are in the same style in red ink.

ff. 9r-16v, 38r, 53r-53v, 86r-97v, 128r-131r, 241r were copied by Ioannes Moschos (Hand C) (RGK I 203, II 279, III 336), in a mixed minuscule script, slanting slightly to the left, in brown ink, with moderate variation in letter size.
Syllabic abbreviations and superscript word endings appear throughout the line. Breathings are round and mute iota is absent. Use of the double dot is functional only.
The modern eta, modern nu, sigma telikon and loop epsilon are present.
Punctuation used includes the lower, middle and upper points, lower and middle commas, question mark and full stop.

decoDesc.decoNote: A slender headpiece in red ink precedes the beginning of the text on f. 19r.
Many sections begin with minor initials in red ink, appearing within the line of text as well as at the beginning of lines.
Some other sections begin with minor initials in brown ink.
Spaces have been left in places for minor initials that were never added (e.g. ff. 9r-15v).

additions.p: Hand B has added marginal scholia both to folios copied by this hand and those copied by Hand A, including a diagram on f. 73v, ση(μείωσαι) marks highlighting notable passages and manicules (e.g. ff. 69r, 117r-118v, 126v).
There are occasional marginal notes in Greek by other hands (e.g. ff. 19r, 87v, 88v-89v, 92v-93r).
Notes in Latin regarding content, by two different hands, appear on ff. 1r, 9r, 18v-19r, 38v, 86r, 104r, 108v, 116r, 121r, 128r, 130r. A list of contents has been added to f. 241r.
On f. 19r is the name Tho(ma)s Bingus.

binding.p: 18th-century full leather binding over millboards, with reverse calf covering on spine and plain pastedowns. There is a blind tooling outline on both boards. The edges have been painted red.
binding.condition: A small portion of leather is missing from the upper board exposing millboard beneath. Spine and board edges are heavily scuffed.

accMat.p: The left endleaf f. [ii] is a stub of parchment manuscript waste with traces of writing in black ink on it.
The following left endleaves ff. [iii-v] are a stub and then two full folios made of printed book waste.

Pasted to f. 1r is a slip of paper bearing a printed note recording that the manuscript came from the gift of Thomas Nevile: Dono ornatissimi viri Thomae Nevile Decani Cantuariensis, et Collegii Trinitatis Praefecti.

history.origin: This manuscript was copied in the late 15th or early 16th century, as indicated by the watermarks and the period of activity of the identified scribes.
history.acquisition: Donated to Trinity College by Thomas Nevile (d. 1615) Nevile, Thomas, -1615 , Dean of Canterbury and Master of Trinity.
